biography: New York City, one story at a time. Created by Brandon Stanton. Dear New York now available wherever books are sold. Order below:

latestPosts.caption: Dear New York closes on October 19th. It’s been the honor and joy of my life to see this take flight. It’s been a magical six days of community and connection, and we have some extra special moments coming in the final week. Thanks to all of you who have made the pilgrimage to Grand Central these last few days. And I hope to see many more of you as the clock ticks down to the closing ceremony next Sunday.  Note: The Vanderbilt Hall exhibit is closed today for a prescheduled event, but will reopen tomorrow and remain open until the conclusion of the installation.

The first copies of Dear New York have arrived. This one is deeply personal; holding it in my hand is like holding three years of my life. it opens with a longform HONY story— think Tanqueray, think Detra, think Venus— except this time it’s the story of my own attempt to capture the people of this city. The book then expands into four hundred full-color portraits and stories. Unlike previous Humans of New York books: 75 percent of these stories have not been shared online. Dear New York was lovingly created to be the most special thing that’s ever come out of Humans of New York. It will make you think, it will make you laugh, it will make you cry. It’s my love letter to this city, and I can’t wait to share it with you this October. But if you could do me a favor: if you think you’ll be getting Dear New York this fall, consider locking in your order now. Preorders have never been more crucial to helping launch a book into the world. The book has yet to be heavily discounted, but I know Amazon and Barnes and Noble specifically will retroactively apply the inevitable future discounts to your order. Thanks everyone! Link in bio.

latestPosts.caption: “We stayed together for two years and realized that we were probably better off as friends than as a couple. Our daughter was two at the time. It was horrible. One day you have access to your child 24/7, and it’s all you’ve known. Then the next day it’s split in half and it’s not always controlled by you. You’re living across the street, but you’re still trying to be the protector. I just didn’t want any trauma. That was the big thing for me: no trauma. Because I grew up with it. I never wanted her emotionally needing me, crying herself to sleep: ‘Daddy, daddy, daddy.’ And to my knowledge she never has. For me it was about consistency: always showing up, never being late. And staying friends with her mother. That was very important to me. After the initial split I remember it was about sixty weeks in a row of me suggesting to my ex: let’s all go to dinner, let’s all go to dinner. Finally she said yes, and it’s become something we’ve done regularly for the past ten years. Our daughter is twelve now, and we all had dinner the other night. We talked about what’s going on at school. We joked about things. I like to think from the outside we looked like any nuclear family out to dinner. I just think it’s so important for our daughter to consistently see the two of us, being our natural selves, in the presence of each other. I’m not the perfect father. And she’s not the perfect mother. We have different parenting styles, and we disagree on a lot of things. But I don’t think we’ve ever been jerks to each other. My ex would always cover for me if I travelled, and I travel a lot, because I work for a Swedish paper mill. I know it was hard for her a lot of times. But if she asked me to cover a weekend, even if I had other plans, I’d agree. And we’ve never used access as a weapon. Even if we were in the middle of a disagreement—we both had access to our daughter every day. We would never say: ‘This isn’t your day’ or ‘This isn’t your week.’ Technically it’s not my week right now, but I’m on the way to pick up my daughter from school. I’m going to take her for a quick snack, and then I’m going to drop her off at her mom’s.”

latestPosts.caption: “Ten years ago I met a professional flower girl. She was 24-years old. She was going through a tough time, so my husband and I tried to help her. We let her use this space. We laid out all the money: transportation, allowance, everything. I worked alongside her in the shop. But the flower girl, she always party. She took the $3,000 I gave her and disappeared. It’s OK. She was young, whatever. We were going to close the shop, but my husband said: ‘You are always happy when you are here, why don’t you run it yourself?’ So that’s what I did. I used to be a fashion designer, so I’m very good with color. I know composition naturally. And also— everything I touch, it grows. People think it’s a miracle. It’s not a miracle. It’s just a matter of caring. When your customer authorizes you to do something, do the best you can offer. People are not dumb. They can see how much thought and time you put into your work. They can tell if you are like crocodile, doing as little as possible, trying to eat all the money you can. Look at all the shops up and down the street—you can see who puts their heart into it. Look at the plants in front of the store. If the plants are dying, the business is dying. It’s a matter of caring. You must care for everything around you. First, I take care of myself. That is most important. I’m seventy-one. If my muscles feel pain, I stop. I’ll do my stretching. Then I care for my husband. He’s a very good partner. Two years ago he had a stroke; he has some minor health things still. So I care for him. We adopted two little kitties. We make them delicious food like human food: turkey, chicken, fish. They grow very big. We take good care of them. Then we care for our friends, our customers, even our customer’s dogs. If you treat your customers’ dogs well, they will smell you and remember you. Everything is together: plants, animals, humans. If you care, you will grow. But not enough people care. It’s not that they aren’t smart. It’s that they want to try everything, so they never care enough about any one thing. Too many choices. Me? This is my only choice. Come by anytime, I’m around.”

latestPosts.caption: “I ran for City Council ten years ago in Eastern Queens, and a young man named Zohran Mamdani volunteered for my campaign. We were both part of a huge immigrant community of South Asian Muslims. Our community is such an important part of this city, but at the time we were not considered to be reliable voters. And that perception came with consequences. After 9/11 there were legal abuses against Muslims that would not have happened to any other community—because we lacked political power. Our campaign set out to transform the electorate. We tried to turn nonvoters into voters. Both of us were young: I was thirty-one, Zohran was twenty-three. And while most of our friends were out partying, we knocked on thousands of doors. But we learned that it’s the hardest sale in the world to make people care as much as you do. In the end I lost badly to a candidate endorsed by the Democratic political machine. The experience left me feeling jaded. There were times I wondered if the only way for a candidate to win was to work within a political machine. But here’s the problem with machines—they don’t have clear values. Our campaign had clear values: we wanted to bring power to people who didn’t have power. But the machine is already powerful, and it only cares about maintaining power. It’s not about new thinking. It’s not about change. If you become their candidate, you must give them loyalty regardless of their positions, and too many times those positions come from special interests. The whole process can make you cynical, which is why these last few months have been so emotional for me. This time around I was the one supporting Zohran, as campaign counsel. I’m filled with pride for what he’s achieved, using many of the lessons we learned ten years ago. I have no problem saying he’s a tremendously better candidate than I ever was. He speaks to people in ways I never could. But his success has given new meaning to all our hard work, so many years ago— knocking on doors, meeting with community elders. My campaign might not have been the swing of the axe that knocked down the tree— the first swing rarely is. But it turns out we were breaking ground for something bigger.”

latestPosts.caption: “A few years back I did a whole art show where the pieces were made of leather. I stapled the shit out of them until they were puffy and weird, like muscles filled with blood. Then I covered them with jewels. Didn’t sell a lot of them. Most people thought ‘What the fuck are these?’ At the opening of the show I noticed two women talking quietly to each other: one of them was full-figured, the other one was old. So I decided to eavesdrop. And they must have gone to art school, because I heard the big one say: ‘Look at these, they’re so beautiful. But they do nothing.’ I never went to art school, so I thought ‘Oh shit, they found out how stupid I am.’ It made me feel so dumb. When I was a kid I had a big head, a football head. I had to wear a helmet. And this woman gave me that ‘football head feeling’ all over again. I wanted to slug her. I wanted to scream: ‘My art does nothing? What the fuck is it supposed to do, vacuum your house?’ But my mother taught me to never burn a bridge. So instead of blowing it out my mouth, I took a deep breath. I said to myself: ‘Just wait, wait a minute. Gestate with negative things, like a shaman. Like a little magic man.’ I said to myself: ‘Maybe they’re right. Wouldn’t it be great if my paintings could do something?’ A few weeks later I ended up finding an old man named Carl who has a hoard of crystals that he sells by the pound. All of Carl’s crystals have healing ‘goo goo’ in them, so I bought $5,000 worth. You see? By holding my tongue, I got something. Those women gave me a gift with their bitchery. Now my paintings can heal and dazzle you at the same time.”

latestPosts.caption: “I’ve decided to go back to school today; I was just accepted into college, and I made the decision to enroll. I happened to be wearing my Coney Island shirt, so I decided to come out here and sit by the water. I used to come out here all the time. For many years I was in an extremely difficult marriage. I’d never say anything hurtful about my ex-wife, because there’s still a lot of love there— but there were times when I had to get away. And this is where I’d go. I ended up leaving the marriage right before the pandemic. I had to completely start over. I went from having my own apartment, and having all the things you’re supposed to have, to sleeping on a mattress on the floor. I never stopped teaching my voice and music lessons. I was still expanding, still growing. But I went through a lot of hardship. There was so much responsibility on me. My mother is 94; she has dementia. I was taking care of her too. For the longest time I’ve never had any room for something going on in my own life. So this is a very big thing for me—going back to school. I’m going to major in social work because I’d like to introduce a therapy element to my voice lessons. If I’m being honest, part of the reason is I need more clients. I’m not somebody who has a big retirement saved. I’m turning 65 soon and I’m no longer very competitive in an ageist music world. So money is part of it. But also, voice lessons are such a wonderful tool for self-actualization. I’ve noticed when people are learning to sing, they come up against so many things that are holding them back. They’ll meet with embarrassment. They’ll meet their inner critic. They’ll have moments where they think: that’s too loud, that’s too shrill. But they have to push past it. Because In order to fill the room, you first need a sense of being worthy enough to express yourself. You can’t say: I’m going to sing like this person. No, you’re going to sound like you. There are tools you can learn to sound like the best version of you, but you will sound like you. And it’s such a privilege to be present when people discover that for the first time: you can sing just like yourself, and it can be beautiful.”

latestPosts.caption: I’d like to conclude with one final story that I think captures the spirit of Dear New York. During the final hour before Sunday’s closing ceremony there was no performer scheduled on the Steinway Concert Grand, so I loudly invited everyone in the crowd to take a turn. About six or seven random New Yorkers stepped forward, bravely volunteering for this once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to play the world’s finest piano for a huge crowd of people in Grand Central Station. It was such a joyous and communal experience. Each person played one song. Everyone was at-least-a-little nervous, but everyone nailed it under the brightest possible spotlight. Eventually one of the producers whispered that it was time to wrap up, but before I could tell everyone ‘Goodnight,’ I noticed the tiniest little hand being raised. It belonged to a six-year-old girl wearing a denim jacket, sparkly cowboy boots, and a small plastic princess crown. I knelt down and asked her name; she told me ‘Charlotte.’ I asked Charlotte if she wanted a chance to play, and she nodded with conviction. Her mother— half-proud, half-terrified—quickly told me that Charlotte had a keyboard at home, but had never played piano before. This small distinction did not bother Charlotte one bit. With the confidence of Liberace, she marched up to the Steinway, took a seat, and played piano for the very first time, in front of hundreds of people. I’m not sure anyone beyond the first row could hear it. But I am sure that everyone could feel it. Immediately following her performance, two hundred young singers from The Young People’s Chorus of New York City brought Dear New York to a close with an epic performance. (Video clip in carousel.) Thank you Charlotte, thank you @ypcofnyc, and thank you everyone, for being such an important part of Dear New York.

latestPosts.caption:
I chose to make this video because Dear NY was genuinely one of the most beautiful and impressive things I’ve seen in the city. @humansofny pulled off something I didn’t think was possible. To put its scale in perspective:

- The MET sees about ~5.7M visitors per year
- MoMA about ~2.7M annual visitors 
- Statue of Liberty ~4.2M annual visitors 

And Dear New York passed them all in foot traffic, in less than two weeks!

Props to Brandon and the team for creating a moment that’ll live on in New York’s history.

#newyork #nyc #grandcentralstation

How does a two-week art installation about community grow into something like this? I think it’s because people are tired of ‘connecting’ through screens. Nobody wants to live in a metaverse, whatever the hell that is. We don’t want to become passive consumers of songs that ‘seem’ human, art that ‘seems’ human, friends that ‘seem’ human. None of this stuff is what we need. We need to create. We need to connect. We need to serve other people if we’re going to have any sort of place or belonging in this world. If humanity is going to thrive— and if art is going to thrive – there is only one place for it to go: the real world. Dear New York was founded upon the increasingly rare belief that humanity is pretty freaking amazing. This isn’t a perfect world. Every day the media brings us new examples of glaring injustice and senseless violence. We still have much work to do. But while we do the work, let us not forget how much love there is in this world. In New York City alone, in a single day, there are millions of stories of people taking care of each other. These stories don’t make the evening news, but they’re no less real. And when you sum it all up—the good and the bad – humanity is still worth fighting for. It’s still something to celebrate. Dear New York will close tomorrow at 8 pm, with a short choral performance by hundreds of children from @ypcofnyc .

latestPosts.caption: Last night someone asked me what part of Dear New York I’m proudest of; this was hard to answer. But I can tell you what’s filled my heart the most. Many in the press are calling it ‘The Children’s Exhibit,’ because Dear New York’s Vanderbilt Hall features the work of six hundred NYC student artists. Each student was asked to photograph and write about someone who has made a difference in their lives. Some of these artists are as young as four, and their photography might not be the most technically polished, but there is a striking intimacy that can only come from photographing someone you love. The written profiles which accompany the photographs are extremely touching, and collectively represent the millions of invisible, unsung heroes that form the bedrock of NYC’s community. It’s not the mayors and the movie stars that form the heart of this city. It’s the mothers, the fathers, the teachers, the social workers, and the millions of other people who show up every day in the lives of others. One reason the ‘Children’s Exhibit’ lands so deeply is that its amplified by a sister exhibition featuring eleven highly notable NYC photographers. Among them are living legends such as @jamelshabazz , a trailblazer in street portraiture. As well as Gugenheim Fellow @sarabennettbrooklyn , a former public defender who profiles formerly-incarcerated women. The two exhibits are blended seamlessly in an innovative, immersive design by @davidkorins . The most beautiful part of these blended exhibits is that all 611 artists— young and old, beginning and established— have been given the same museum-quality framing and presentation. The result is an egalitarian, non-hierarchical ode to the diversity, humanity, and community of this city.  The exhibit has been overflowing all week, from open to close, and I’m not sure I’ve ever seen an art installation elicit so much emotion. Dear New York closes on Sunday. For everyone who attends the final Sunday, you will be able to meet all eleven featured professional artists, who will be there to greet visitors between 2 pm and 5 pm.
